1.1 Defining and interpreting Delta E

E - (Delta E, dE) is the eucledian distance between two color spots. It is a metric that encodes a numeric understanding how the human eye perceives color difference. The word Delta defines a difference between two spots while E comes from the German Word Empfindung.

In this Analysis the E76 vaue was calculated which got his name from the year it was founded, which was 1976.

The formular is

E76 = sqrt((L)^2 + (a)^2 + (b)^2)

where:

L = L1 L2 - difference of luminance.

a = a1 a2 - difference of values for coordinate a, b = b1 b2 - difference of values for coordinate b.

b = b1 b2 - difference of values for coordinate b.

On a typical scale, the Delta E value will range from 0 to 100.
E value Perception
<= 1.0 Not perceptible by human eyes.
1 - 2 Perceptible through close observation.
3 - 10 Perceptible at a glance.
11 - 49 Colors are more similar than opposite
100 Colors are exact opposite

2 Analysis

2.1 How do colors behave relative to the print master?

It can be seen that the colors have the same relation to the print master. While it is evidently, that there is always one color with the smallest E value regarding the print master, the biggest error almost always appears at the same color spot, too.

The mean Error relative to the print master is comparatively low, as the followng density plot is showing.

The density of E value shows the highest error between 3.5 and 4. It is compared to the master data and perceptible at glance.

2.2 Is the behavior differential between targets?

One target is a sigle color card on one sample sheet. One sample can be seen as a big sheet containing 42 color cards. The behavior inbetween the targets is very similar, which is also shown in the relation to the print master discussed in the previouse section. The mean E value per target does not show a big range. It ranges from 3.6 to 4.2, which still is at glance.

2.3 Is the behavior differential between color spots?

2.4 Is quality possibly related to the intended color?

Since the minimal E values, as well as the maximum E values always appear on the same color spot, the Error seems to be very much related to the intended color.
